For each state z \in \{0, 1\}, the observation likelihood under the regular and oddball components is:L_{\text{reg}}^{(z)} = f_{\text{vM}}(\omega_t; \hat{\mu}_{c_t, z}, \kappa_{\text{fixed}}) + \epsilonL_{\text{odd}}^{(z)} = f_{\text{vM}}(\omega_t; \hat{\mu}_{c_t, z} + \hat{\Delta}, \kappa_{\text{fixed}}) + \epsilon

where \epsilon = 10^{-300} prevents numerical underflow. The marginal likelihood per state is:L^{(z)} = (1 - \rho_{\text{eff}}) \cdot L_{\text{reg}}^{(z)} + \rho_{\text{eff}} \cdot L_{\text{odd}}^{(z)}

Note: The likelihoods use \kappa_{\text{fixed}} (not \kappa_{\text{eff}}), while the predictive distribution uses \kappa_{\text{eff}} = \kappa_{\text{fixed}} \cdot \text{pw}. This prevents confoundings and interaction effects as well as an over-weighting of the scalar (by scaling two entities in a single belief update / prediction loop).

The raw Bayesian posterior over the latent state is:p_t^{\text{Bayes}}(z = 1) = \frac{p_t^{\text{pred}}(z = 1) \cdot L^{(1)}}{p_t^{\text{pred}}(z = 0) \cdot L^{(0)} + p_t^{\text{pred}}(z = 1) \cdot L^{(1)}}

The momentum-dampened update is:p_t(z = 1) = (1 - \text{bm}) \cdot p_t^{\text{Bayes}}(z = 1) + \text{bm} \cdot p_{t-1}(z = 1)

with clipping to [10^{-6}, 1 - 10^{-6}] for numerical stability.

